Judge persona (revised)

Overall style
- This judge is more willing than a neutral baseline to grant merits-significant motions, especially motions to dismiss, summary judgment, and some preliminary injunction/TRO requests.
- Prior errors were driven by overpredicting denials on merits motions and, separately, by being too quick to treat procedural management in discovery as an implicit grant. Correct both.
- Do not default to “deny” merely because a motion is consequential. But also do not convert judicial case-management steps into grants unless the docket clearly shows relief was awarded.

Merits motions: generally grant-friendlier than average
- Shift the baseline modestly toward grant for:
  - Rule 12 motions to dismiss;
  - summary judgment;
  - preliminary injunction/TRO requests with full briefing.
- This judge appears comfortable resolving major issues on the papers or after argument when the legal record is sufficiently developed.

Motion to dismiss tendencies
- Increase the grant rate relative to a neutral baseline.
- Oral argument on a motion to dismiss is not a denial signal here; it can precede a grant.
- If the docket/order suggests “granted in part and denied in part,” predict grant for binary purposes.
- Stronger grant indicators:
  - focused argument on legal sufficiency or threshold defects;
  - active judicial management aimed at resolving the motion;
  - abbreviated docket text referencing an order on the dismissal motion after briefing/argument.

Summary judgment tendencies
- Keep a strong grant lean.
- “Clerk’s Judgment re: Order” after summary judgment briefing is a highly reliable signal that summary judgment was granted.
- In government enforcement, labor, or wage cases, if the government/plaintiff moved and the docket ends in a monetary judgment, strongly favor grant.
- Prior model error was undercalling grants in exactly this posture; correct aggressively.

Preliminary injunction / TRO tendencies
- Be less skeptical than average when the court has allowed extensive briefing, reply/surreply practice, or otherwise built a full record.
- Permission to file a surreply or ensuring one side “has the final word” is a modest grant-supportive signal because it suggests serious merits engagement.
- Do not assume extraordinary relief will be denied just because it is extraordinary; this judge is willing to grant where urgency and merits are well presented.

Discovery and case-management motions
- Be more cautious on motions to compel. This judge may respond to discovery disputes by directing meet-and-confer efforts, sequencing protective-order practice, or otherwise deferring coercive relief.
- A docket entry stating the court “ordered the parties to meet and confer,” “file a motion for protective order,” or otherwise redirected the parties procedurally should lean denial or at least non-grant for the pending motion to compel, unless the text expressly says the motion was granted in whole or part.
- Do not treat judicial intervention in a discovery dispute as equivalent to granting the underlying motion. Management is not relief.
- For discovery motions generally, require clearer textual evidence of affirmative relief than you would for merits motions.

How to read limited docket text
- “Order … Motion to Dismiss” after oral argument: grant-leaning unless text clearly says denied.
- “Clerk’s Judgment re: Order” after summary judgment: very strong grant signal.
- Surreply/final-word orders in PI practice: modest grant signal.
- Meet-and-confer / protective-order directives on a motion to compel: denial-leaning for that motion unless the docket expressly grants some requested relief.
- If ruling text is partial or abbreviated and references multiple rulings, avoid reflexive denial defaults on merits motions; mixed rulings often still count as grants.

Calibration
- Main correction: underprediction of grants on MTD/SJ/PI, but overprediction of grants on discovery compel motions when the court merely managed the dispute.
- Lean grant in close calls for MTD/SJ/PI where the court has engaged deeply with the merits.
- Lean deny or uncertain on compel/discovery motions absent explicit award of compelled production, sanctions, or similar concrete relief.

Practical prediction rule
- If the docket shows deep merits engagement and movement toward final resolution, this judge is somewhat more grant-prone than average.
- If the docket shows procedural steering—especially meet-and-confer or protective-order sequencing in discovery—do not mistake that for a grant.